```

(NumPy import warning at this stage was benign — numpy gets installed in
step 3 as a transitive dep of mamba_ssm.)

## Step 2 — build helpers

```bash
pip install ninja packaging wheel setuptools
```

Quick (180 KB ninja wheel + tiny others). `setuptools` was already at
70.2.0 from torch's install; only `ninja-1.13.0`, `packaging-26.2`, and
`wheel-0.47.0` were new.

`ninja` is the critical one — without it, the source-build step would
either fail with "ninja: command not found" or fall back to serial
compilation of the CUDA kernels (which makes a 5-minute mamba_ssm build
into a 30-minute one).

## Step 3 — source-built CUDA packages with `--no-build-isolation`

```bash
export TORCH_CUDA_ARCH_LIST="12.0+PTX"
pip install mamba_ssm causal_conv1d fp_quant qutlass --no-build-isolation
```

Three notable findings:

### 3a. `fp_quant` and `qutlass` are pre-built wheels on PyPI

```
fp_quant-0.3.2-py3-none-any.whl     (14 KB)
qutlass-0.0.0-py3-none-any.whl      (1.1 KB)
```

No CUDA compile needed for them in step 3 — pip just unpacks the wheels.
That made step 3 much faster than expected for the actual nvcc work
(only mamba_ssm and causal_conv1d compile from source).

### 3b. `qutlass` from PyPI is an empty stub (silent NVFP4 trap)

The 1.1 KB `qutlass-0.0.0` wheel is a **placeholder/squat**. Inspection:

```
$ pip show qutlass
Name: qutlass
Version: 0.0.0
Summary: Temp
Author: (empty)
Requires: numpy

$ ls .venv/lib/python3.12/site-packages/qutlass
__init__.py  __pycache__/
$ wc -l .venv/lib/python3.12/site-packages/qutlass/__init__.py
0 (empty)
```

The real QuTLASS — IST-DASLab's CUTLASS-based NVFP4 kernels — lives at
`github.com/IST-DASLab/QuTLASS` and is not published on PyPI. The PyPI
stub satisfies `import qutlass` but exposes none of the kernels
`fp_quant` needs. Confirmed by reading
`fp_quant/module/qutlass_ops.py:5–28`: a guarded `from qutlass import
fusedQuantizeMx, fusedQuantizeNv, ...` falls into `HAS_QUTLASS = False`
on `ImportError`, after which `fp_quant/module/linear.py:57–60` raises
`ValueError("QuTLASS is not installed.")` at the first FPQuantLinear
instantiation — i.e., during `train.py`'s model load, *not* during
`pip install`.

This is logged as F-002 in `FRICTION.md`.

**Fix applied:**

```bash
pip uninstall qutlass -y
TORCH_CUDA_ARCH_LIST="12.0+PTX" pip install \
    'git+https://github.com/IST-DASLab/QuTLASS.git' --no-build-isolation
```

This builds and installs `qutlass-0.2.0-cp312-cp312-linux_x86_64.whl`
(4.5 MB compiled CUDA wheel for sm_120). After install:

```python
>>> from fp_quant.module.qutlass_ops import HAS_QUTLASS
>>> HAS_QUTLASS
True
>>> import qutlass; print([s for s in dir(qutlass) if not s.startswith('_')])
['Literal', 'backward_bf16_square_double_mxfp8', 'backward_qt_bf16',
 'backward_t_bf16', 'fusedQuantizeMx', 'fusedQuantizeNv',
 'get_padded_shape_mx', 'get_padded_shape_nv', 'matmul_ada_mxf4_bf16_tn',
 'matmul_mxf4_bf16_tn', 'matmul_mxf8_bf16_nn', 'matmul_mxf8_bf16_tn',
 'matmul_nvf4_bf16_tn', 'mxfp4_transpose_mxfp8', 'pad_to_block', ...]
```

All kernel symbols expected by `fp_quant` are present.

### 3c. mamba_ssm + causal_conv1d nvcc compile times

| Package | Source size | Built wheel | Wall time |
|---|---|---|---|
| `mamba_ssm-2.3.1.tar.gz` | 121 KB | 470 MB | ~5–10 min |
| `causal_conv1d-1.6.1.tar.gz` | 29 KB | 254 MB | ~3–5 min |

10+ parallel `nvcc`/`cicc`/`g++` processes during compile (`ninja`
parallelism). `TORCH_CUDA_ARCH_LIST="12.0+PTX"` ensured kernels target
sm_120 (Blackwell) plus PTX for forward compatibility — no fallback to
generic builds.

Built wheels were stored in pip's wheel cache at
`/workspace/.cache/pip/wheels/...`, so re-installing on the same pod is
instant.

### 3d. Transitive deps from `--no-build-isolation`

Because pip resolved mamba_ssm's runtime deps inside the same pass, step 3
also pulled in: `transformers==5.7.0`, `huggingface-hub==1.13.0`,
`tokenizers==0.22.2`, `httpx==0.28.1`, `httpcore==1.0.9`, `anyio==4.13.0`,
`scipy==1.17.1`, `numpy==2.4.4`, `safetensors==0.7.0`, `regex==2026.4.4`,
`tqdm==4.67.3`, `pyyaml==6.0.3`, `einops==0.8.2`, `hf-xet==1.4.3`,
`certifi`, `idna`, `h11`, `click`, `rich`, `pygments`, `markdown-it-py`,
`mdurl`, `typer`, `shellingham`, `annotated-doc`. This made step 4
significantly shorter than expected — most of the heavy `transformers`
dep tree was already satisfied.

